  "game_explanation": "Three players repeatedly make single-proposal trades in a 3-round, 3-turn-per-round schedule. All players value GREEN chips at $0.50 each (common-value), while RED chips have heterogeneous private values (dog $0.30, buffalo $0.10, cat $0.40). That creates a common pattern: proposers tend to want to convert their lower-value REDs into higher-value GREENs (or sometimes convert GREENs into multiple REDs if the exchange ratio is favorable). Recipients evaluate offers based only on their own private red value and current holdings, so they will accept only when the immediate chip-value change is nonnegative. Because acceptance decisions are simultaneous and a proposer cannot choose among multiple acceptors, proposers face uncertainty: making an attractive offer may yield multiple acceptances and a random partner, while making an offer that benefits only the proposer risks unanimous decline. Inventory constraints matter: some trades that are attractive in theory are infeasible if a counterparty lacks enough chips to give. Behavioral priors shape likely choices: dog (exploratory, medium bookkeeping) tends to experiment with exchange ratios; buffalo (high bookkeeping, cautious) prefers structured, predictably profitable exchanges; cat (conciliatory, moderately patient) tends to propose deals likely to be accepted or to extract modest gains. Over the three rounds we expect most successful proposals to be those that (a) improve the proposer’s chip value and (b) offer enough compensation (multiple REDs per GREEN) so at least one counterparty gains value by accepting. When an offer benefits multiple recipients, a random selection determines the partner, which adds strategic risk for proposers.",
