  "game_explanation": "Three-player repeated bargaining with symmetric starting inventories (10 red, 10 green each). Greens are common-value (0.50) for everyone; reds are heterogeneous (badger 0.80, otter 0.30, goose 0.30). That creates consistent opposing incentives: badger strongly prefers accumulating reds, while otter and goose prefer greens. Proposers will tend to request greens and offer reds (since that improves their own value) while badger will often be willing to accept trades that convert greens into reds. Acceptance decisions are private and based on each recipient's own chip values and current holdings: badger will accept many 1-for-1 green-for-red proposals (gain ≈ +0.30), whereas otter and goose only accept when the exchange benefits them (typically accepting red->green, not green->red). Because multiple non-senders can simultaneously accept, some proposals that are attractive to both otter and goose risk random assignment of the recipient; proposers who value control less (or cannot target a partner) must tolerate that risk. Uncertainty arises from two sources: (1) each player only knows their own chip values and must infer others' preferences from public history, and (2) when multiple players accept, the proposer cannot choose which acceptor completes the trade. Given the personas (otter: patient and numerate, low aggressiveness; badger: conciliatory but red-preferring; goose: disciplined and anchor-sensitive) the likely path is repeated small 1-for-1 exchanges: otter/goose repeatedly propose to buy 1 GREEN for 1 RED (gaining for themselves), and badger frequently accepts those proposals because converting green into red is profitable for him. Badger also proposes symmetric 1-for-1 RED-for-GREEN trades to acquire even more reds; those proposals are often accepted by otter and goose because they gain green, but when both accept the recipient is randomly chosen.",
